{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778980474997,"sessionID":"ses_1cc81798affeY6djrRh3to6wSK","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Jk69AZsA94TyqGgn3CiP5fcd","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-uberon/eval-ont-agent-uberon/docs/id-management.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-uberon/eval-ont-agent-uberon/docs/id-management.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # ID management in Uberon\n2: \n3: ## Temporary IDs\n4: \n5: “Temporary IDs” are an experimental mechanism to allow editors to mint\n6: new term IDs without worrying about potential conflicting IDs.\n7: \n8: This is primarily intended for AI agents, which are likely to open many\n9: PRs in parallel but have to share a single ID range (contrary to human\n10: editors, who all have their own range) and have no way of keeping track\n11: of which IDs are being used in concurrent PRs (again contrary to human\n12: editors, who can rely on Protégé for that).\n13: \n14: However temporary IDs are in no way restricted to AI agents, and any\n15: editor could use them if they so want. For example, they could be useful\n16: for an _external_, _occasional_ editor – someone who is not a known\n17: contributor to Uberon and for whom we may not necessarily want to\n18: allocate a dedicated ID range.\n19: \n20: ### Editing the ontology with temporary IDs\n21: \n22: From an editor’s point of view, all that is needed to use temporary IDs\n23: is to use the `Temporary IDs` range defined in the `uberon-idranges.owl`\n24: file.\n25: \n26: For editors using Protégé, this means selecting said `Temporary IDs`\n27: range when Protégé asks you to select an ID range policy, just after\n28: having opened the Uberon edit file.\n29: \n30: For other editors (including AI agents), this means making sure that\n31: whenever a new ID is needed, it is generated within the range allocated\n32: to `Temporary IDs` (it should normally be `UBERON:99NNNNN`, but please\n33: check the contents of the `uberon-idranges.owl` file, just in case the\n34: range is changed in the future).\n35: \n36: ### Replacing temporary IDs with definitive IDs\n37: \n38: Replacing temporary IDs with definitive IDs is done by invoking the\n39: `allocate-definitive-ids` target:\n40: \n41: ```sh\n42: sh run.sh make allocate-definitive-ids\n43: ```\n44: \n45: This will find all temporary IDs within the ontology and replace them\n46: with newly allocated definitive IDs picked from within the `Automation`\n47: range defined in the `uberon-idranges.owl` file. All axioms that were\n48: referring to temporary IDs will be automatically re-written so that they\n49: refer to the corresponding newly allocated definitive IDs.\n50: \n51: This replacement must be performed at the latest possible stage, just\n52: before a PR is merged. If temporary IDs in a PR are replaced by\n53: definitive IDs, and the PR is then left unmerged for a while, then ID\n54: conflicts may occur when the PR is finally merged.\n55: \n56: For convenience, a GitHub Actions workflow is available to perform the\n57: ID replacement step on a PR without requiring a Uberon maintainer to\n58: check out the PR and invoke the `allocate-definitive-ids` manually. When\n59: a PR containing temporary IDs has been deemed OK for merging, a\n60: maintainer should trigger the `allocate-definitive-ids` GitHub Actions\n61: workflow on the PR’s branch, wait for that workflow to terminate (it\n62: should take a couple of minutes at most), and then _immediately_ merge\n63: the PR.\n64: \n65: ### Automatic replacement of temporary IDs upon pushing to master\n66: \n67: Alternatively, a PR containing temporary IDs can be merged “as is” to\n68: the master branch. This will then trigger an automatic ID replacement\n69: operation (made by the same `allocate-definitive-ids` GitHub Actions\n70: workflow), directly on the master branch.\n71: \n72: Compared to the approach above, where the ID replacement is done on the\n73: PR _prior to merging_, this approach has the following advantages:\n74: \n75: * it is entirely automated, and does not require any manual intervention\n76:   from a maintainer;\n77: * it eliminates the risk of an ID conflict still occurring between the\n78:   moment IDs are replaced on a PR and the moment the PR is merged.\n79: \n80: It has the inconvenient that it lets temporary IDs becoming part of the\n81: history of the master branch, which may make perusing the history more\n82: cumbersome as the history will be “polluted” by commits that do nothing\n83: more than rewriting IDs. With the “replace-before-merging” approach,\n84: such commits can be made invisible if the PR is small enough to allow\n85: for a “squash merge” instead of a normal merge – then only the\n86: definitive IDs will only ever make it to the master branch.\n\n(End of file - total 86 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# ID management in Uberon\n\n## Temporary IDs\n\n“Temporary IDs” are an experimental mechanism to allow editors to mint\nnew term IDs without worrying about potential conflicting IDs.\n\nThis is primarily intended for AI agents, which are likely to open many\nPRs in parallel but have to share a single ID range (contrary to human\neditors, who all have their own range) and have no way of keeping track\nof which IDs are being used in concurrent PRs (again contrary to human\neditors, who can rely on Protégé for that).\n\nHowever temporary IDs are in no way restricted to AI agents, and any\neditor could use them if they so want. For example, they could be useful\nfor an _external_, _occasional_ editor – someone who is not a known\ncontributor to Uberon and for whom we may not necessarily want to\nallocate a dedicated ID range.\n\n### Editing the ontology with temporary IDs","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"docs/id-management.md","time":{"start":1778980474982,"end":1778980474995}},"id":"prt_e337fd062001gKnDDV0xjOD4DU","sessionID":"ses_1cc81798affeY6djrRh3to6wSK","messageID":"msg_e337fbe7d001wG05fDGPQn6ELn"}}
